description:
If the default test client adds 'retry_writes => 1' to its config, then t/bulk.t and other tests fails.

One error is that BulkWriteView::delete_many doesn't flag the bulk as non-retryable.  This is easily fixed with:

{noformat}
diff --git a/lib/MongoDB/BulkWriteView.pm b/lib/MongoDB/BulkWriteView.pm
index 7dd0f21f..5710e2cf 100644
--- a/lib/MongoDB/BulkWriteView.pm
+++ b/lib/MongoDB/BulkWriteView.pm
@@ -121,7 +121,6 @@ sub _update {
     }

     $self->_bulk->_retryable( 0 ) if $method eq 'update_many';
-    $self->_bulk->_retryable( 0 ) if $method eq 'delete_many';

     my $update = {
         q      => $self->_query,
@@ -140,6 +139,7 @@ sub _update {

 sub delete_many {
     my ($self) = @_;
+   $self->_bulk->_retryable( 0 );
     $self->_enqueue_write(
         [
             delete => {
{noformat}

After that change, there is another failure where a WriteConcern error is received at a place where a DuplicateKeyError is received.

Try::Tiny is very slow compared to a core-only idiom:
{noformat}eval {
  whatever();
  1;
} or do {
  my $error = $@ || 'Zombie error';
  ...
};
{noformat}
We've already removed it from several hot code paths, but we should eliminate it entirely.

If a URI like below is used:
{code}
my $client = MongoDB->connect('mongodb+srv://a1:<pwd>@cluster0-5b9kh.mongodb.net/test?ssl=true');
{code}
The driver crashes with:
{noformat}
MongoDB::UsageError: expected boolean string 'true' or 'false' for key 'ssl' but instead received '1' at /usr/local/share/perl/5.26.1/MongoDB/_URI.pm line 200.
	MongoDB::_URI::_parse_options(MongoDB::_URI=HASH(0x558110203658), HASH(0x55811099ab10), HASH(0x55811021e620)) called at /usr/local/share/perl/5.26.1/MongoDB/_URI.pm line 389
	MongoDB::_URI::BUILD(MongoDB::_URI=HASH(0x558110203658), HASH(0x5581109a08e0)) called at (eval 446) line 306
	MongoDB::_URI::new(undef, "uri", "mongodb+srv://a1:pwd\@cluster0-5b9kh.mongodb.net/test?ssl=true") called at /usr/local/share/perl/5.26.1/MongoDB/MongoClient.pm line 1226
	MongoDB::MongoClient::_build__uri(MongoDB::MongoClient=HASH(0x55810fe51810)) called at (eval 386) line 21
	MongoDB::MongoClient::_uri(MongoDB::MongoClient=HASH(0x55810fe51810)) called at /usr/local/share/perl/5.26.1/MongoDB/MongoClient.pm line 1324
	MongoDB::MongoClient::BUILD(MongoDB::MongoClient=HASH(0x55810fe51810), HASH(0x55811029e8d0)) called at (eval 445) line 992
	MongoDB::MongoClient::new(undef, HASH(0x55810e1881e0)) called at /usr/local/share/perl/5.26.1/MongoDB.pm line 71
	MongoDB::connect("MongoDB", "mongodb+srv://a1:pwd\@cluster0-5b9kh.mongodb.net/test?ssl=true") called at ./quicktour.pl line 13
{noformat}

A non-SRV URI works fine though:
{code}
my $client = MongoDB->connect('mongodb://a1:<pwd>@cluster0-shard-00-00-5b9kh.mongodb.net:27017,cluster0-shard-00-01-5b9kh.mongodb.net:27017,cluster0-shard-00-02-5b9kh.mongodb.net:27017/test?ssl=true&replicaSet=Cluster0-shard-0&authSource=admin&retryWrites=true');
{code}

The regular expression in MongoDB::_URI to sanitize during stringification is a bit limited.  It won't cover "mongodb+srv://" URIs and might not terminate if the path slash is missing.  Possible better would be
{noformat}
^([^:]+)://[^/?]*\@
{noformat}

DRIVERS-626 added pipeline support to update operations.  The Perl driver did this for update_one and other MongoDB::Collection methods, but didn't make the same adjustments in MongoDB::BulkWriteView and there were no tests in the spec for this.

Example failing program:

{noformat}
#!/usr/bin/env perl
use v5.10;
use strict;
use warnings;
use utf8;
use open qw/:std :utf8/;

use MongoDB;
use BSON::Types ':all';

my @data = (
    {
        "_id" => 1,
        "x"   => 1,
        "y"   => 1,
        "t"   => { "u" => { "v" => 1 } }
    },
    {
        "_id" => 2,
        "x"   => 2,
        "y"   => 1
    },
);

my $pipeline = bson_array(
    { '$replaceRoot' => { "newRoot" => '$t' } },
    { '$addFields'   => { "foo"     => 1 } },
);

my $mc=MongoDB->connect();
my $coll=$mc->ns("test.foo");
$coll->insert_many(\@data);

my $bulk = $coll->ordered_bulk;
$bulk->find({_id => 1})->update_one($pipeline);
{noformat}

 

BSON::XS module for Perl has a memory leak in the C code that is running _always_ when document has subdocument, i.e. contains a nested hash (or IxHash):
{code:java}
my $hash = {
    'nested' => {
        'key' => 'str',
    }
};
{code}
The following C structure is currently used to trace circular references on hashes:
{code:java}
 typedef struct _stackette {
   void *ptr;
   struct _stackette *prev;
 } stackette;
{code}
New stackette is allocated for every document and its subdocuments.

But to free this structure it is not enough to call
{code:java}
Safefree(stack);{code}
on first stackette, because all next stackettes remain not free and their addresses get lost.

 

I tried to code less and came up with the solution to improve stackette structure to keep all next references that can be used to free next stackettes in right place.

The patch is available here: [https://github.com/develdot/mongo-perl-bson-xs/commit/4932d3677805c4608ccfc4b3cfdd473e663c7771]

The Perl code that shows the problem with memory in the latest version 0.8.2 of BSON::XS is attached.

From https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-php-driver/pull/808/files#r22467817:

{quote}
If we compare this ({{php_mongo_runcommand()}}) with the {{php_mongo_collection_findone()}} code above, we're calling {{php_mongo_handle_error()}} before loading the current element. Effectively, the {{$err}} check will be ignored and we'll only handle errors if the error flag bit is set on the cursor. Is this an oversight?

The code path in {{php_mongo_collection_findone()}} ({{php_mongo_handle_error()}} after {{php_mongocursor_load_current_element()}}) looks correct.
{quote}
